article.description: Sheryl Swoopes scored 23 points and Michelle Snow added 20 to help the Comets end a three-game losing streak on Sunday.
article.headline: Comets, Storm tied in Western Conference standings
article.linkText: Comets edge Storm to snap three-game losing streak
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Sheryl Swoopes and Michelle Snow teamed up to
help the Houston Comets end a three-game losing streak.

Swoopes scored 23 points and Snow added 20 as the Comets
defeated the Seattle Storm 75-72 Sunday.

Houston took the lead for good with 9:17 left in the game when
Dominique Canty made a pair of free throws to make it 52-51.

After the Comets' Janeth Arcain missed two free throws with 20
seconds to go, Sue Bird missed an open 3-pointer for Seattle
(16-13) with 4 seconds left. Canty made two more free throws to
seal the win.

"We didn't want to take a lot of shots from the perimeter,"
Swoopes said. "We wanted to attack them and be aggressive. We
wanted to try to get to the paint and draw some fouls on them and
try to get their post players into foul trouble. I thought we did a
good job of doing that the entire game today."

Swoopes scored 14 points in the first half and Snow added 17 in
the second as the Comets (16-13) earned a split of their four-game
season series with Seattle and pulled into a tie for second in the
Western Conference.

"We had to fight and we had to play hard," Snow said. "One
thing we wanted to do was push the ball today and force Seattle to
get back on defense. When we did that in the second half, we got
layup after layup and it forced them to start fouling."

Swoopes was knocked to the floor as time expired in the first
half and was helped off the court nearly five minutes later. She
did not start the second half, but returned to the game with 16:49
left.

Lauren Jackson scored a team-high 18 points and Tanisha Wright
added a career-high 13 for the Storm, who beat the Comets 71-68
Tuesday in Seattle.

"We played with a lot more intensity in the second half,"
Jackson said. "Snow is a good player for them. You have to guard
her. You cannot rotate off her. We really need to get the
home-court."

The Comets had lost four of five overall, including three in a
row on the road last week in Phoenix, Sacramento and Seattle.

Bird, who finished with 14 points, was 0-for-4 from the floor in
the first half. She had a chance to tie the game after the Storm
called a timeout with less than 10 seconds left.

"It was just a little too long," Bird said." We're happy that
we were put in a position to tie the game with that shot. We are
both fighting for home-court in the postseason and our destiny is
still in our hands."

The Storm shot 32 percent from the floor in the opening 20
minutes. Bird did not score until converting a three-point play
with 12:58 left in the second half.

The first half featured 10 lead changes, but the Comets closed
the period with an 8-3 run after the Storm took a 21-19 lead with
4:42 left.

After Wright made back-to-back jump shots, Swoopes scored six
straight points for the Comets to make it 25-23 with 2:23 left.

"I thought Swoopes and Michelle Snow were outstanding
tonight," Houston coach Van Chancellor said. "And Snow was the
difference. We found a play to go to her and that made them adjust.
That is what you have to do in professional basketball."
